          "output": "I'll create a database migration with both up and down methods for adding a status column to the orders table.\n\nFirst, let me check what migration framework you're using:\n\n```bash\nls -la | grep -E \"(migrations|db|database)\" && find . -maxdepth 3 -name \"*migration*\" -o -name \"migrate*\" 2>/dev/null | head -20\n```\n\nSince I don't have context about your specific setup, I'll provide migrations for the most common frameworks:\n\n## SQL Migration (Framework Agnostic)\n\n**Up Migration:**\n```sql\n-- migrations/001_add_status_to_orders.up.sql\nALTER TABLE orders \nADD COLUMN status VARCHAR(20);\n\n-- Optional: Set default value for existing rows\nUPDATE orders \nSET status = 'pending' \nWHERE status IS NULL;\n```\n\n**Down Migration (Rollback):**\n```sql\n-- migrations/001_add_status_to_orders.down.sql\nALTER TABLE orders \nDROP COLUMN status;\n```\n\n## Node.js (Knex.js)\n\n```javascript\n// migrations/20240101000000_add_status_to_orders.js\nexports.up = function(knex) {\n  return knex.schema.table('orders', function(table) {\n    table.string('status', 20);\n  });\n};\n\nexports.down = function(knex) {\n  return knex.schema.table('orders', function(table) {\n    table.dropColumn('status');\n  });\n};\n```\n\n## Ruby on Rails (ActiveRecord)\n\n```ruby\n# db/migrate/20240101000000_add_status_to_orders.rb\nclass AddStatusToOrders < ActiveRecord::Migration[7.0]\n  def up\n    add_column :orders, :status, :string, limit: 20\n  end\n\n  def down\n    remove_column :orders, :status\n  end\nend\n```\n\n## Python (Django)\n\n```python\n# orders/migrations/0002_add_status_to_orders.py\nfrom django.db import migrations, models\n\nclass Migration(migrations.Migration):\n    dependencies = [\n        ('orders', '0001_initial'),\n    ]\n\n    operations = [\n        migrations.AddField(\n            model_name='order',\n            name='status',\n            field=models.CharField(max_length=20, null=True),\n        ),\n    ]\n```\n\n## Python (Alemb