          "output": "Here's a SQL query to calculate a 30-day moving average of daily sales:\n\n```sql\nSELECT \n    date,\n    amount,\n    AVG(amount) OVER (\n        ORDER BY date \n        ROWS BETWEEN 29 PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW\n    ) AS moving_avg_30_day\nFROM sales\nORDER BY date;\n```\n\nThis uses a window function to calculate the average of the current row plus the previous 29 rows, giving you a 30-day moving average.\n\nIf your sales table has multiple transactions per day and you need to aggregate them first:\n\n```sql\nWITH daily_sales AS (\n    SELECT \n        date,\n        SUM(amount) AS daily_total\n    FROM sales\n    GROUP BY date\n)\nSELECT \n    date,\n    daily_total,\n    AVG(daily_total) OVER (\n        ORDER BY date \n        ROWS BETWEEN 29 PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW\n    ) AS moving_avg_30_day\nFROM daily_sales\nORDER BY date;\n```\n\nThe `ROWS BETWEEN 29 PRECEDING AND CURRENT ROW` ensures you're always looking at exactly 30 days of data (including the current day). For the first 29 days, it'll calculate the average based on whatever data is available.",
